EATF is a reference implementation and specification for cryptographically
verifiable AI agent self-attestation. It does NOT constitute a trust
service under eIDAS Article 3(16) of Regulation (EU) 910/2014. Tyche
Institute does not issue qualified certificates, signatures, timestamps,
or attestations as a service to external customers and does not operate
as a Qualified Trust Service Provider. EATF agent attestations are
technical self-attestations and do not constitute Qualified Electronic
Attestations of Attributes (QEAA) under eIDAS Article 3(45).

This product references but does not include the following technical
standards and reference materials, which remain the property of their
respective publishing organisations:

- IETF RFC 3161 (Time-Stamp Protocol)
- IETF RFC 5280 (Internet X.509 Public Key Infrastructure)
- IETF RFC 8785 (JSON Canonicalization Scheme)
- NIST FIPS 204 (Module-Lattice-Based Digital Signature Standard)
- W3C Verifiable Credentials Data Model 2.0
- OVERT 1.0 (Observable Verification Evidence for Runtime Trust)

Standards-relationship classification is documented in docs/architecture.md
under the legend IMPLEMENTED / ALIGNED / REFERENCED / ADDRESSED.
